The paper deals with distributed algorithms for sampling and counting problems on graphs, which falls under the category of distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in the form of joint distributions and marginal probabilities. The paper uses techniques from computational complexity (cs.CC) to establish equivalences between different tasks. The paper also involves graph theory and combinatorics (cs.DS) in the form of graph problems and feasible solutions. Finally, the paper uses concepts from statistical physics and machine learning (cs.LG) in the form of spatial mixing and inference.
